{"title_page": "Danny Coulson", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|name = Danny Coulson\n|image = D.Coulson_Wiki.jpg\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1941|06|29}}\n|birth_place = [[Texas]]\n|death_date = \n|death_place =\n|occupation = Security consultant\n|salary =\n|networth = \n|website =\n| education = Bachelor's degree in Government, [[Texas Christian University]]<br><br>Law degree, Southern Methodist University<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smu.edu |title=smu.edu |publisher=smu.edu |date=2011-11-18 |accessdate=2012-01-14}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Daniel O'Neal Coulson''' (born June 29, 1941) is a former Deputy Assistant Director of the [[FBI]].  In his thirty-year tenure at the FBI, Coulson created and commanded the FBI\u2019s [[Hostage Rescue Team (FBI)|Hostage Rescue Team]]<ref>{{cite web\n|year=2008\n|url= http://www.aeispeakers.com/speakerbio.php?SpeakerID=641\n|title=Coulson Danny \u2013 AEI Speakers Bureau\n|publisher=[[American Entertainment International Speakers Bureau, Inc]]\n|accessdate=2008-05-23\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n|year=2001\n|url= http://www.paulagordon.com/shows/coulson\n|title=Danny Coulson on The Paula Gordon Show\n|publisher=[[The Paula Gordon Show]]\n|accessdate=2008-05-23\n}}</ref> and commanded four field divisions.\n\nAs of Spring 2009, Danny Coulson is a successful security consultant, author, and guest speaker.<ref>{{cite web \n |year=2008 \n |url=http://www.internationalspeakers.com/speakers/ISBB-55358M/Danny_Coulson \n |title=Danny Coulson speaks for International Speakers Bureau \n |publisher=International Speakers Bureau \n |accessdate=2008-05-23 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070813121245/http://www.internationalspeakers.com/speakers/ISBB-55358M/Danny_Coulson/ \n |archivedate=2007-08-13 \n }}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |year=2008 \n |url=http://www.rothtalent.com/speakers/slist/coulson \n |title=Roth Talent Associates: Danny Coulson \n |publisher=[[The Agency Group, Ltd.]] \n |accessdate=2008-06-03 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516062959/http://www.rothtalent.com/speakers/slist/coulson/ \n |archivedate=2008-05-16 \n}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nDanny received his bachelor's degree in Government from [[Texas Christian University]]. He then attended [[Southern Methodist University]] where he earned his [[Law degree|Law Degree]]. He passed the [[Bar examination|Texas Bar]].\n\nCoulson worked for the next nine years in the FBI's New York Division, where he specialized in Police Assassination, Fugitive, and Bank Robbery Investigations. Additionally he served on the FBI's [[Sniper team|Sniper Team]] and commanded one of the most active [[Swat Team|SWAT Teams]] in the FBI.\n\nIn 1982, after a rise through the ranks of the FBI, Coulson was assigned to create the Hostage Rescue Team ([[Hostage Rescue Team|HRT]]).<ref>{{cite book |last=Pushies |first=Fred J.|author2=Terry Griswold |author3=D. M. Giangreco |author4=Stephen F. Tomajczyk |title=[[U.S. Counter-Terrorist Forces]]|publisher=[[Crestline Imprints]]|year=2002 |isbn=0-7603-1363-6|quote=The first commander of the Hostage Rescue Team was Danny Coulson. (Subsequent commanders were David \"Woody\" Johnson, Richard Rogers, and Roger Nisley.) Coulson was selected because he was a good street agent, possessed a law degree, and had tactical experience as a SWAT Team member in New York.|page=305}}</ref> While in command of HRT, Coulson personally negotiated the surrender of domestic terrorists at Mountain Home, AR, without any loss of life. For his actions, Coulson received the [[Attorney General]]'s Award for Exceptional Service.\n\nIn 1984, Coulson led a team of FBI agents to [[Whidbey Island]] to arrest [[Robert Jay Mathews]], the leader of the neo-Nazi terrorist group [[The Order (white supremacist group)|The Order]]. Mathews was killed in the resulting shootout.\n\nIn 1986 Coulson was the Inspector In Charge of the [[Iran Contra]] Investigation for the FBI and later headed up the same investigation for Independent Counsel [[Lawrence E. Walsh|Judge Lawrence Walsh]].\n\nIn 1987, Coulson was the tactical commander at the [[Atlanta Prison Riots]]. That situation culminated with the release of over a hundred hostages.  He has secured the release of over two hundred and seventy five hostages in his career.\n\nAs deputy assistant director of the FBI's Criminal Investigation Division, Coulson managed all investigations of violent crimes, and terrorism worldwide, as well as civil rights and special inquiries for the White House.\n\nAs Special Agent in Charge (SAC) of the FBI office in Dallas, Texas, he was detailed as one of the Commanders of the [[Oklahoma City bombing]] investigation.\n\nIn 1997, upon retiring from the FBI, Coulson created a private security firm, Coulson, Jackson and Associates, assisting law firms and international corporations. Additionally he handles security matters for some of the most high-profile athletes in the United States.\n\nIn 1999, Coulson admitted that the FBI had used pyrotechnic grenades at the [[Waco siege]], contradicting previous reports.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hancock|first=Lee |date=August 24, 1999|title=2 Pyrotechnic Devices Fired at Davidians, Ex-official Says|newspaper=Dallas Morning News}}</ref> \n\nWhile residing in Texas, Coulson co-authored ''No Heroes: Inside The FBI's Secret Counter-Terror Force''<ref>{{cite web|last=Haney |first=Eric |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/0671020625 |title=No Heroes: Inside the FBI's Secret Counter-Terror Force (9780671020620): Daniel Coulson, Sharon Shannon: Books |publisher=Amazon.com |accessdate=2012-01-14}}</ref> with Elaine Shannon of [[Time (magazine)|''Time'']].<ref>{{cite news|date=April 13, 1999|url=http://www.cnn.com/chat/transcripts/coulson.html|title=CNN \u2013 Chatpage \u2013 Books \u2013 Danny Coulsen|publisher=CNN|accessdate=2008-05-23}}</ref>\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coulson, Danny}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Federal Bureau of Investigation executives]]\n[[Category:Southern Methodist University alumni]]\n[[Category:Texas Christian University alumni]]\n[[Category:Oklahoma City bombing]]\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|name = Danny Coulson\n|image = D.Coulson_Wiki.jpg\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1941|06|29}}\n|birth_place = [[Texas]]\n|death_date = \n|death_place =\n|occupation = Security consultant\n|salary =\n|networth = \n|website =\n| education = Bachelor's degree in Government, [[Texas Christian University]]<br><br>Law degree, Southern Methodist University<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smu.edu |title=smu.edu |publisher=smu.edu |date=2011-11-18 |accessdate=2012-01-14}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Danny Coulson''' (born June 29, 1941) is a former Deputy Assistant Director of the [[FBI]].  In his thirty-year tenure at the FBI, Coulson created and commanded the FBI\u2019s [[Hostage Rescue Team (FBI)|Hostage Rescue Team]]<ref>{{cite web\n|year=2008\n|url= http://www.aeispeakers.com/speakerbio.php?SpeakerID=641\n|title=Coulson Danny \u2013 AEI Speakers Bureau\n|publisher=[[American Entertainment International Speakers Bureau, Inc]]\n|accessdate=2008-05-23\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n|year=2001\n|url= http://www.paulagordon.com/shows/coulson\n|title=Danny Coulson on The Paula Gordon Show\n|publisher=[[The Paula Gordon Show]]\n|accessdate=2008-05-23\n}}</ref> and commanded four field divisions.\n\nAs of Spring 2009, Danny Coulson is a successful security consultant, author, and guest speaker.<ref>{{cite web \n |year=2008 \n |url=http://www.internationalspeakers.com/speakers/ISBB-55358M/Danny_Coulson \n |title=Danny Coulson speaks for International Speakers Bureau \n |publisher=International Speakers Bureau \n |accessdate=2008-05-23 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070813121245/http://www.internationalspeakers.com/speakers/ISBB-55358M/Danny_Coulson/ \n |archivedate=2007-08-13 \n }}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |year=2008 \n |url=http://www.rothtalent.com/speakers/slist/coulson \n |title=Roth Talent Associates: Danny Coulson \n |publisher=[[The Agency Group, Ltd.]] \n |accessdate=2008-06-03 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516062959/http://www.rothtalent.com/speakers/slist/coulson/ \n |archivedate=2008-05-16 \n}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nDanny received his bachelor's degree in Government from [[Texas Christian University]]. He then attended [[Southern Methodist University]] where he earned his [[Law degree|Law Degree]]. He passed the [[Bar examination|Texas Bar]].\n\nCoulson worked for the next nine years in the FBI's New York Division, where he specialized in Police Assassination, Fugitive, and Bank Robbery Investigations. Additionally he served on the FBI's [[Sniper team|Sniper Team]] and commanded one of the most active [[Swat Team|SWAT Teams]] in the FBI.\n\nIn 1982, after a rise through the ranks of the FBI, Coulson was assigned to create the Hostage Rescue Team ([[Hostage Rescue Team|HRT]]).<ref>{{cite book |last=Pushies |first=Fred J.|author2=Terry Griswold |author3=D. M. Giangreco |author4=Stephen F. Tomajczyk |title=[[U.S. Counter-Terrorist Forces]]|publisher=[[Crestline Imprints]]|year=2002 |isbn=0-7603-1363-6|quote=The first commander of the Hostage Rescue Team was Danny Coulson. (Subsequent commanders were David \"Woody\" Johnson, Richard Rogers, and Roger Nisley.) Coulson was selected because he was a good street agent, possessed a law degree, and had tactical experience as a SWAT Team member in New York.|page=305}}</ref> While in command of HRT, Coulson personally negotiated the surrender of domestic terrorists at Mountain Home, AR, without any loss of life. For his actions, Coulson received the [[Attorney General]]'s Award for Exceptional Service.\n\nIn 1984, Coulson led a team of FBI agents to [[Whidbey Island]] to arrest [[Robert Jay Mathews]], the leader of the neo-Nazi terrorist group [[The Order (white supremacist group)|The Order]]. Mathews was killed in the resulting shootout.\n\nIn 1986 Coulson was the Inspector In Charge of the [[Iran Contra]] Investigation for the FBI and later headed up the same investigation for Independent Counsel [[Lawrence E. Walsh|Judge Lawrence Walsh]].\n\nIn 1987, Coulson was the tactical commander at the [[Atlanta Prison Riots]]. That situation culminated with the release of over a hundred hostages.  He has secured the release of over two hundred and seventy five hostages in his career.\n\nAs deputy assistant director of the FBI's Criminal Investigation Division, Coulson managed all investigations of violent crimes, and terrorism worldwide, as well as civil rights and special inquiries for the White House.\n\nAs Special Agent in Charge (SAC) of the FBI office in Dallas, Texas, he was detailed as one of the Commanders of the [[Oklahoma City bombing]] investigation.\n\nIn 1997, upon retiring from the FBI, Coulson created a private security firm, Coulson, Jackson and Associates, assisting law firms and international corporations. Additionally he handles security matters for some of the most high-profile athletes in the United States.\n\nIn 1999, Coulson admitted that the FBI had used pyrotechnic grenades at the [[Waco siege]], contradicting previous reports.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hancock|first=Lee |date=August 24, 1999|title=2 Pyrotechnic Devices Fired at Davidians, Ex-official Says|newspaper=Dallas Morning News}}</ref> \n\nWhile residing in Texas, Coulson co-authored ''No Heroes: Inside The FBI's Secret Counter-Terror Force''<ref>{{cite web|last=Haney |first=Eric |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/0671020625 |title=No Heroes: Inside the FBI's Secret Counter-Terror Force (9780671020620): Daniel Coulson, Sharon Shannon: Books |publisher=Amazon.com |accessdate=2012-01-14}}</ref> with Elaine Shannon of [[Time (magazine)|''Time'']].<ref>{{cite news|date=April 13, 1999|url=http://www.cnn.com/chat/transcripts/coulson.html|title=CNN \u2013 Chatpage \u2013 Books \u2013 